Here's what happens when you scan the WhatsApp QR code with your phone:

How It Works (whatsapp-web.js library):

QR Code Generation — The backend (server/whatsapp.js) launches a headless Chrome browser via Puppeteer and opens web.whatsapp.com. WhatsApp Web generates a QR code that the server captures and converts to a base64 image.

Scanning with Phone — In your WhatsApp mobile app, you go to Settings → Linked Devices → Link a Device and scan the QR code displayed in the admin portal.

Authentication — The QR code contains a session token. When scanned, WhatsApp's servers authenticate the browser session and link it to your phone account.

Session Persistence — The LocalAuth strategy saves session data to ./.wwebjs_auth/ folder. After the first successful scan, the server remembers the session and won't need a QR code again (unless you disconnect or the session expires).

Ready State — Once authenticated, the ready event fires. The backend status changes to ready and the QR code disappears. The server can now:

Send WhatsApp messages to members
Check if phone numbers are on WhatsApp
Receive message status updates
API Endpoints:

GET /api/whatsapp/status — Check connection state (disconnected, connecting, qr, ready)
GET /api/whatsapp/qr — Get the current QR code image (base64 data URL)
POST /api/whatsapp/disconnect — Log out and clear the session
Important Notes:

Your phone must stay connected to the internet. If your phone is offline, the web session stops working.
The QR code refreshes every ~20 seconds if not scanned.
Only one WhatsApp session can be active at a time per server instance.
The session is tied to the phone number you scan with — so make sure you scan with the SAYEF organization's WhatsApp number, not a personal one.

